"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=world+news+site:telegraph.co.uk/us","Trump-Ramaphosa latest: Trump and Musk meet South African president in Oval Office","https://www.telegraph.co.uk/us/politics/2025/05/21/trump-musk-meet-ramaphosa-oval-office/","Wed, 21 May 2025 16:41:39 GMT","

Donald Trump ambushed Cyril Ramaphosa with videos of what he said was persecution of white South Africans as the two leaders met in the Oval Office.

Mr Trump told the South African president that white farmers were being “persecuted” and “fleeing” the country, demanding an “explanation” for what he said was a “very sad situation”.

“We have thousands of stories talking about it, we have documentaries, we have news stories... it has to be responded to,” the US president said.

Narrating over the footage, having dimmed the lights in the Oval Office, he continued: “These are burial sites right here, over a thousand of white farmers and those cars are lined up to pay love on a Sunday morning.”

Mr Trump then flicked through a series of news articles in front of Mr Ramaphosa about “white South Africans... fleeing because of the violence and racist laws”. He added, looking at one story: “This family was wiped out.”

The people “being persecuted” are “generally... white farmers and they're fleeing South Africa and it's a very sad thing to see”, Mr Trump said, telling Mr Ramaphosa: “I hope we have an explanation of that, because I know you don't want that.”

Donald Trump's meeting with Cyril Ramaphosa in the Oval Office in front of media is now over.

A trade union leader who is part of Cyril Ramaphosa's delegation was called to speak.

She insisted that issues within South Africa were more to do with crime, than race, citing the murder and rape of black women in the country.

Donald Trump nodded along as she spoke, and did not interrupt.

South African golfer Ernie Els tells Donald Trump about growing up during apartheid, adding: “Two wrongs don't make a right”.

The former world number one says: “We wanted to come here to meet you and see the way forward [and] see our nation flourish.”

Donald Trump described a genocide under way in South Africa.

“We have hundreds of people, thousands of people, trying to come into our country because they feel they're going to be killed and their land is going to be confiscated,” he said in the Oval Office.

In fact the first flight that arrived from South Africa last week carried just 59 people. They flew on a Boeing 767 chartered by the Trump administration, leaving most of its 270 seats unoccupied.

Cyril Ramaphosa is trying to steer the conversation back to the economy and away from persecution claims, saying his “main reason” for being in the US is to “foster trade and investment”.

That will allow them to “address these societal problems”, he continues, saying people turn to crime when they are unemployed and “have no other hope”.

John Steenhuisen, the minister for agriculture in South Africa, has insisted that the majority of white farmers want to stay in South Africa.

He said that the attacks on farms must also be treated as priority crimes, and that the views of Julius Malema and Jacob Zuma, whom Mr Trump showed videos of, do not represent the views of the current government.

He said that his party, the Democratic Alliance, has joined hands with Mr Ramaphosa's government, of the African National Congress party, to “keep those people out of the union”.

Cyril Ramaphosa, the South African president, knew it would be a tricky meeting. The Trump administration last week gave refuge to Afrikaner farmers amid wild accusations that they were the victims of a genocide and land seizures.

But he may not have reckoned with Donald Trump's sense of theatre.

“Turn the lights down and just put this on,' he said, as journalists and leaders alike craned to watch an explosive video of Julius Malema, leader of a fringe communist party, dancing and singing an anti-Apartheid song entitled “Kill the Boer, the farmer.”

Mr Trump accused his guest of failing to protect white South Africans as Mr Ramaphosa tried to keep his cool, explaining that his government had nothing to do with Mr Malema.

That may be so, and Mr Trump's grasp of South African politics might be weak, but once again he had used the intimate setting of the Oval Office to drive home his point.

Donald Trump pointed to Elon Musk during his Oval Office meeting with Cyril Ramaphosa, the president of South Africa, although he admitted he “did not want” to get “Elon involved”.

He said: “I know many people from South Africa...Elon is from South Africa. But I don't want to get Elon involved. He actually wanted to talk about a different subject, sending rockets to space.”

Speaking over Mr Ramaphosa, the US president added: “I would say that people are fleeing South Africa for their own safety, their land is being confiscated and they are being killed.”

