The cruel truth about the video game industry is that there are simply too many releases trying to grab the audience's attention. With an ever-growing timeline of titles, spanning back further and further, it seems that some real gems may fall through the cracks. That's natural, considering it takes longer to play a game than it might to watch a movie or binge a TV show. This type of interactive entertainment benefits tremendously from word of mouth, though, with players passing their recommendations on to each other, in the hope that a game might find its footing when that effect begins to snowball.

Of course, for those games that span back much further, fans need to listen to the experts. Luckily, one well-respected critic and video game developer has pointed audiences in the direction of Ico, a fantastic game from 2001 which still hasn't garnered the attention that it so sorely deserves. So, this is a good opportunity to dive into why Hideo Kojima recommended this old-school title at all and how it has actually gone on to influence the video game industry in general. Because this was a game that carried such quality, it inspired a whole generation of developers, with a studio set up in its honor. Ico might not be overly easy to find and play today, considering it was launched on the PlayStation 2, but retro gamers should absolutely hunt out this lost icon.

Hideo Kojima, known for his work on Death Stranding, Metal Gear Solid, and Snatcher, has created quite the reputation. Because gamers and movie buffs alike look to the creator for his opinion on just about anything. His film reviews have become the stuff of legend at this point, with Kojima refusing to say anything at all about the movies he feels fail to live up to expectations. But if the developer gets behind a film, like Wallace & Gromit: Vengeance Most Fowl, then the world is going to know about it.

Well, back in 2001, Hideo Kojima got behind a video game that would soon fade into the history books, despite his love for the title. The game, as established, was Ico, and Hideo Kojima has named it as one of the greatest games ever made. In fact, Kojima was so heavily influenced by the title that he claims that it has actually impacted his own work, citing that the visuals in games like Metal Gear Solid directly draw from this gameplay experience.

And he's not the only one to do so. Several other creators have also shared in this adulation for Ico and its visual palette, which is cinematically rich and always focused on narrative above all else. Ico has shaped a whole generation of designers, but it also had a profound impact on the team that worked on the game.

Metal Gear Solid was a genre-defying work of video game artistry, and it still holds up as the most game-changing entry in Konami's iconic franchise.

The game was developed by Sony Computer Entertainment Japan, a company that would eventually go on to host the studio known as Team Ico, which worked on Shadow of the Colossus and The Last Guardian. The studio was full of like-minded geniuses, all content to continue experimenting within their small area of the industry. A few notable names worked on Ico, including director Fumito Ueda, who also directed on Team Ico's two other notable releases, and producer Kenji Kaido, who also worked on the Tomba! and the Ape Escape series, among others.

Famous composer Michiru Ōshima put together the score for the game, having established himself in anime and on games like Legend of Legaia, and eventually The Legend of Zelda: Twilight Princess. The title's voice acting cast further elevated the piece, with Kazuhiro Shindō appearing as Ico, Rieko Takahashi starring as Yorda, and Misa Watanabe playing the Queen. The team behind Ico is essentially full of significant talents who prove that they are so much more than the sum of their parts when they are brought together. Perhaps that's why Ico had such an effect on so many other storytellers. Because it was a showcase piece of what the best are capable of when collaborating.

So, Hideo Kojima might have had some fond words to say about Ico, and the team behind the hit is of great value, but what about the forgotten PlayStation 2 game actually made it such a must-play experience? Well, Ico began with a stunning premise that saw players take control of the titular boy, after he is taken away to be sacrificed by a group of warriors. It's a haunting start, but one that allows Ico to escape and battle back in a heroic display. While exploring the castle he has been abducted to, Ico finds a girl called Yorda, who is also imprisoned here and somehow connected to the fortress itself.

With unexplainable powers and a good heart, Yorda proves to be the perfect ally, as the duo maintains their distance from the ominous Queen. When it's revealed that the Queen won't let them escape because she believes she can live out a new life within Yorda, her supposed daughter, Ico, is forced to finally confront the forces of evil head-on. It's a story dripping in tension and drama, but one that also possesses real heart as Ico and Yorda build their bonds in the most difficult of situations. Narratively, this is a standout piece of work, but the development team always supported that storytelling with their own expert mechanics and visuals.

Hideo Kojima shared some thoughts about being a creative online, and it has some fans wondering about his future in games.

Graphically, Ico wasn't breaking any new ground, especially when relying on the technology of the PlayStation 2. But there's real scope and ambition to the castle players explore, and a sense of world-building whenever a new area is accessed. This always felt like a real, breathing world, where everything has a purpose. That's further supported by the character models and asset designs, with NPCs packing personality, and weapons and other background objects always taking on a slightly stylized aesthetic. The true strength of this title is its cinematic lighting, which adds grandeur to every scene, especially with complex key frame animation.

Ico also relied upon classic platform level design, with intriguing puzzles to solve, and a third-person camera rig that always moved in unexpected ways. With minimal dialogue throughout, the action had to do so much of the talking, and Yorda and Ico's relationship is thus further built by how the player must help Yorda navigate the castle via the gameplay mechanics. What's especially fascinating is that the player is therefore constantly defending Yorda from the enemy, too, with the combat elements focused on that dynamic. Some versions of the game even provide a 2-player option, which reinvents the experience all over again.

Ico's legacy is one of risk-taking and looking for ways to add wrinkles to a genre that perhaps had been seen a little too often. It excels in its mission, and it's no wonder that so many creatives feel that the legacy of the game is so powerful. Indeed, all of those who were influenced by the title are still adding to Ico's fingerprint, its very DNA is changing by how the industry is still influenced by it. Unfortunately, Ico was never a commercial hit, with the difficult PlayStation 2 game overlooked even at the time of its release. But the critics always smiled down upon its inventive spirit.

The use of bloom lighting also changed the industry, with the effect becoming a more standard inclusion after what Ico achieved. It wasn't that surprising that, after so many had said such good things about Ico, the game would be revisited in an HD remaster that could truly advance those visuals. In 2011, 10 years on from its release, an HD version of Ico was released on the PlayStation 3; a version of the game that should be a lot more accessible for modern audiences. The game soon also became available on the PlayStation Vita, albeit with a couple of adjustments.

The production of Metal Gear Solid almost came to a screeching halt.

As of this writing, there do not appear to be any plans to return to Ico again, either for a full-on remake or a sequel. However, PlayStation has been particularly interested in its own history as of late, and perhaps Ico's role in that will be recognized again, despite it never quite forming the connection with audiences that developers hoped it would be able to cement. But players who are interested in the legacy of this title, its impact on the industry, and why it came to have such an effect on creators like Hideo Kojima should know that this title deserves a moment of their time. It has, without a doubt, one of the most moving finales to any video game, resulting in a truly satisfying encounter.

