"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=women's+us+soccer","Emma Hayes's USWNT roster includes a first-timer who waited quite a while","https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2025/05/20/uswnt-roster-loeau-labonta/","Wed, 21 May 2025 01:11:37 GMT","

Lo'eau LaBonta, known for her tenacious play and colorful personality, was among 24 players invited to USWNT training camp ahead of friendlies against China on May 31 and Jamaica on June 3.

In just one year of coaching the U.S. women's national soccer team, Emma Hayes has extended close to two dozen first-time invitations to training camp. Most have gone to young players seeking a place in the talent pool as the 2027 World Cup draws closer.

At 32, Lo'eau LaBonta did not seem to figure into Hayes's plans. A 10-year NWSL midfielder, the 5-foot-1 LaBonta had built a fine pro career and a big following among fans enamored with her tenacious play and colorful personality.

The Sports Moment newsletter

Tuesday brought a new accolade: a U.S. call-up.

LaBonta was among 24 players named by Hayes to training camp ahead of friendlies against China on May 31 in St. Paul, Minnesota, and Jamaica on June 3 in St. Louis.

“With the volume of young players or less experienced players we're bringing in, I think we have to get that balance right,” Hayes said. “Someone like Lo who, I mean, she's a super player and someone [who] is deserving of that [call-up]. This is the right moment to do it.”

If she plays, LaBonta will become the oldest player to debut in the program's 40-year history. A third of the way through the NWSL season, she has captained and scored three goals for the Kansas City Current, which leads the league with a 7-2-0 record.

LaBonta's only international experience has been with the under-14, under-15 and under-23 squads.

LaBonta was among three invitees who have never played for the national team, joining Seattle Reign goalkeeper Claudia Dickey and Orlando Pride defender Kerry Abello, both 25.

Last month, Phallon Tullis-Joyce, a 28-year-old goalkeeper from Manchester United, made her U.S. debut in a 2-0 victory over Brazil.

This camp marks the return of Chelsea's Naomi Girma, a world-class center back who has yet to play this year because of a calf injury. Other veteran call-ups include midfielders Lindsey Heaps and Sam Coffey, defenders Crystal Dunn and Emily Fox and forward Lynn Biyendolo.

Four of the seven forwards on the roster are 22 or younger. Four teenagers received invitations: midfielders Lily Yohannes (17), Olivia Moultrie (19) and Claire Hutton (19) and winger Gisele Thompson (19).

No members of the vaunted “Triple Espresso” front line are on the squad. Trinity Rodman received an excused absence from the Washington Spirit after reinjuring her back this spring, and Sophia Wilson and Mallory Swanson are on maternity leave.

Hayes said she speaks with Rodman regularly but does not know when she will return.

“We want to ensure she's not carrying that pain any further, and I think we're definitely heading in the right direction,” Hayes said. “I don't know when she will be back, but I know Trin is being given all the support by everyone, and we very much hope for a speedy recovery.”

Midfielder Rose Lavelle and defender Tierna Davidson are unavailable because of injuries.

The U.S. Soccer Federation is also planning to announce an under-23 roster Wednesday for two away friendlies against Germany in the coming weeks.

