The location couldn't be more fitting, for the facility sits next to the Djokovic foundation's headquarters and pays homage to its namesake's tennis roots. The end goal of the complex's opening aligns with Djokovic's ongoing mission to encourage future generations to fully embrace an active lifestyle, and follows in the footsteps of similar Lacoste initiatives that included collaborations with Gustavo Kuerten and Daniil Medvedev.“Those are the some of the courts in which I grew up playing junior tournaments. It was a great job done by creative artists and something that was very close to my heart, obviously,” Djokovic reflected with TENNIS.com. “It's a way of giving back to the community, contributing to better and more exciting access to public courts.“I always have been and I always will be a proponent of outdoor activities. Trying to get young children and young people out on the courts, sports facilities, fields, trying to engage in as many outdoor activities as possible. There's no better, healthier environment or development for them to do so.”

