"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=Cryptid+Sightings","Bigfoot sightings in Ohio? Try to catch a glimpse during Salt Fork Squatchin'","https://www.daily-jeff.com/story/sports/outdoors/2025/05/20/bigfoot-sightings-in-ohio-hike-for-cryptid-at-salt-fork-state-park/83574676007/","Wed, 21 May 2025 00:33:48 GMT","

LORE CITY − Be it Bigfoot, Sasquatch, Yeti, Grassman or any other name, they all refer to the large, furry, humanoid creature rumored to hide in the woods.

Regardless of what you call this mysterious mythical creature, here in Ohio or somewhere else in the world, there is a large contingent of true believers in the state and around the country.

And so, the search continues year after year for the legendary creature as his popularity seems to grow.

In Ohio, a true sign that another summer Bigfoot exploration season is underway starts with the annual Ohio Bigfoot Conference, which took place at the Salt Fork State Park Lodge in early May.

The conference has been held for more than 30 years with the first meeting held in 1989 by Don Keating in Newcomerstown, Ohio. 

Current owner/organizer Marc DeWerth took over the organization from Keating during the 2012 season and made the move to Salt Fork State Park.

""Our mission statement has always been to educate folks on the probability and possibility that Bigfoot or Sasquatch does in fact roam the Ohio woodlands,"" DeWerth said. ""Our goal of the event is to have a fun, family friendly environment for people to come to that gives them an opportunity to learn more about Bigfoot in a positive manner.""

Salt Fork Park naturalist John Hickenbottom, a local authority on and self-proclaimed Bigfoot enthusiast, feels the real attraction of the conference is the opportunity to meet other Bigfoot fans.

""To me the core of the conference is getting to meet other Bigfoot folks,"" Hickenbottom said. ""Getting together with other individuals in the Bigfoot community ... that's the core reason to attend the conference to me. You get to spend a weekend with people who are interested in Bigfoot.

""I mean, you would have to consider interest in Bigfoot to be a fringe amount of the population. Well now, by attending the conference, you get to mingle, meet and talk with around 3,000 people who share your interest in the 'Big Guy.'""

A group of over 3,000 Bigfoot enthusiasts were estimated to be in attendance for this year's event, which featured an impressive list of guest speakers, including Ranae Holland and Cliff Barackman of Finding Bigfoot, which is an American reality television series on Animal Planet that follows a team of four researchers investigating potential evidence for Bigfoot, a human or ape-like mythical creature.

Many of the visitors taking in the conference took the opportunity to tour the brand-new Salt Fork Eco-Discovery Center, especially with the bigfoot-centric nature of the EDC, which opened to the public in April.

""Everyone loved how we handled Bigfoot here in the Discovery Center, by using him as an education tool for the children and a focal point of the center,"" Hickenbottom, who oversees the daily operations of the EDC, said. ""Everyone was thrilled with it, and I received all kinds of compliments and positive impact from people.""

Visitors to the Eco-Discovery Center can check out the Ohio Bigfoot Hall of Fame that the Ohio Bigfoot Conference created back in 2012. The EDC is now the permanent home of the Ohio Bigfoot Hall of Fame with the official Hall of Fame plaque proudly displayed inside.

'We created the Ohio Bigfoot Hall of Fame in 2012 with the idea that it was time to start giving recognition to the early pioneers of Ohio's Bigfoot research community,"" DeWerth said. ""These individuals who took the time to investigate and document Ohio's vast Bigfoot history.

""Making the Eco-Discovery Center its home is a perfect place for it to be displayed so people truly understand that Ohio does in fact have a huge history when it comes to the Bigfoot phenomenon.  ""

Interested in getting out into the woods and trying to catch a glimpse of the elusive Bigfoot? Then make plans to attend popular bigfoot hikes called Salt Fork Squatchin'

The hikes begin shortly after Memorial Day and are held monthly until around September.

""It is family friendly (not scary) Bigfoot hike that we call Salt Fork Squatchin', and there is no pre-registration and free of charge,"" said Hickenbottom, who organizes the hikes. ""Visitors get to learn about the legend of Bigfoot here at Salt Fork and some of the research techniques that Bigfoot researchers use out in the field. They also learn about nocturnal animals, owls, coyotes, etc., ecology and habitat.

""We try to schedule them so it's just getting true dark as we are leaving the woods.""

For more information on Salt Fork Squatchin', contact naturalist John Hickenbottom at 740-630-6105 or john.hickenbottom@dnr.ohio.gov.

The Salt Fork Squatchin' schedule will also be listed on Salt Fork State Park's Facebook page.

See you in the woods!

