Donald Trump ambushed Cyril Ramaphosa during their Oval Office meeting with footage he said showed white South Africans being persecuted.

In an extraordinary confrontation, the US president ordered staffers to dim the lights and play a video showcasing what he called a genocide of white farmers in the country.

Turning to Mr Ramaphosa, the South African president, Mr Trump said people “were fleeing” while demanding an “explanation” for what he said was a “very sad situation”.

“We have thousands of stories talking about it, we have documentaries, we have news stories... it has to be responded to,” the US president said.

Narrating over the footage, he continued: “These are burial sites right here, over a thousand of white farmers and those cars are lined up to pay love on a Sunday morning.”

“Those cars aren't driving. They're stopped there to pay respects to their family member who was killed, and it's a terrible sight. I've never seen anything like it.”

Visibly uncomfortable, Mr Ramaphosa appeared to turn away to speak to the US president, who in turn pointed at him to implore him to continue watching.

Mr Trump accused Pretoria of carrying out a “genocide” against white Afrikaner farmers, allegations South Africa has vehemently denied.

After being shown the clips of what Mr Trump claimed were black South Africans making racist speeches and singing “kill the Boer” about white people, Mr Ramaphosa told Mr Trump: “This is not government policy.”

Confronting Mr Ramaphosa in the Oval Office, Mr Trump said: “You're taking people's land. And those people, in many cases, are being executed. They're being executed and they happen to be white, and most of them happen to be farmers, and that's a tough situation.”

Earlier this month the Trump administration admitted 59 white South Africans as refugees who have claimed they have been discriminated against because of their race.

After the footage had finished playing, Mr Trump began flicking through a series of news articles printed out on A4 paper showcasing apparent white persecution.

“Death, death, death, horrible death,” he said as he examined the stories.

Meanwhile, South African native Elon Musk, who has increasingly been absent from the White House in recent weeks, watched on in silence.

Pointing to him during the exchange, Mr Trump admitted he does not want” to get “Elon involved”, suggesting it was too dangerous.

He said: “I know many people from South Africa... Elon is from South Africa. But I don't want to get Elon involved. He actually wanted to talk about a different subject, sending rockets to space.”

There were moments of levity sprinkled throughout the press conference, with conversation intermittently turning to golf.

Mr Ramaphosa was flanked by some of South Africa's top golfers in the Oval Office, including Ernie Els.

Els, a former world number one is friends with both men and is understood to have been instrumental in persuading Mr Trump to set up the meeting with the South African president.

Mr Trump cut off aid to South Africa over allegations the country was mistreating its minority white population. Washington also expelled the country's ambassador, accusing him of being a “race-baiting politician” who hates the US and Mr Trump.

Experts in South Africa say there is no evidence of white people being targeted, although farmers of all races are victims of violent home invasions in a country that suffers from a very high crime rate.

The South African leader had sought to use the meeting to set the record straight and salvage his country's relationship with the United States which is at its lowest point since South Africa enforced its apartheid system of racial segregation, which ended in 1994.

Mr Trump has falsely accused the South African government of a rights violation against white Afrikaner farmers by seizing their land through a new expropriation law. No land has been seized and the South African government has pushed back, saying US criticism is driven by misinformation.

The Trump administration's references to the Afrikaner people — who are descendants of Dutch and other European settlers — have also elevated previous claims made by Mr Musk that the South African government is allowing attacks on white farmers in what amounts to a genocide.

