"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=atp+tennis","ATP Seeks Dismissal of Players' Antitrust Lawsuit","https://www.sportico.com/law/analysis/2025/atp-tour-motion-to-dismiss-pospisil-lawsuit-1234853330/","Wed, 21 May 2025 19:56:42 GMT","


							By 

	Michael McCann


Legal Analyst and Senior Sports Legal Reporter


	The ATP Tour on Tuesday motioned for the dismissal of an antitrust lawsuit brought by the Professional Tennis Players Association (PTPA) and a group of players including Vasek Pospisil, Nick Kyrgios and Anastasia Rodionova. The motion was brought to a Southern District of New York judge on grounds that a clause in the ATP's bylaws states that any claims be heard in Delaware.


	The case, which was brought in March, accuses the ATP Tour, WTA Tour, the International Tennis Federation (ITF) and the International Tennis Integrity Agency (ITIA) of conspiring to suppress players' earning and other professional opportunities. Among alleged forms of collusion include agreements to cap prize money, policies that unfairly limit revenue shares with players and requirements that players sometimes compete in excessive heat and other dangerous conditions.

	











	In a brief authored by Bradley Ruskin and other attorneys from Proskauer Rose, the ATP aims to persuade U.S. District Judge Margaret M. Garnett to enforce a forum selection clause, which dictates where disputes will be heard, and toss the case.


	As told by the ATP, male tennis players can only compete if they sign a form that says they agree to comply and be bound by ATP bylaws, resolutions and rules. Relevant here is an ATP forum selection clause contained in the association's bylaws stating that “the Delaware Courts shall have exclusive jurisdiction over any dispute or controversy between any Claiming Party and the League or any member.”


	The ATP insists this clause is enforceable and meets relevant legal criteria. To that point, the ATP says the clause was “reasonably communicated” to players, who had a chance to review materials before signing. The clause is also described as visible to readers, and “as prominent as all other sections.” It is also referenced in the table of contents. The ATP further asserts the clause is mandatory, not permissive, since it uses the word “shall”, and that it covers “any dispute or controversy” meaning it is without limit in governing types of claims.


	In addition, the ATP insists the clause is “not unreasonable, unjust or invalid.” The clause can't be regarded as “fundamentally unfair,” the ATP argues, since the ATP is an international organization—meaning it could be sued in jurisdictions both in and outside the U.S. —and therefore has a “valid interest in limiting any suits brought against it to a single, convenient forum.”

	











	The ATP's brief also seeks the dismissal of claims that pertain to women tennis players. The ATP says it does not conspire with the WTA, which oversees women's tennis, and that they operate in separate markets since they compete for players of different sexes.


	In a separate motion to dismiss authored by Heather P. Lamberg and other attorneys at Freshfields, the ITIA says it is not a proper party in the lawsuit. The ITIA stresses its “mission is to safeguard the integrity of professional tennis by overseeing the anti-doping and anti-corruption rules” and that it would not be involved in any agreement to “monopsonize the market” for men's and women's tennis players. But in the complaint, the ITIA is described as using “aggressive, unrelenting, and, at times, illegal investigative processes subject players to dozens of drug tests (both blood and urine), invasive searches of their personal cell phones, hours-long interrogations without counsel, and harassment by unaccountable and ill-trained investigators.”


	In response to these filings, PTPA executive director Ahmad Nassar told Sportico, “There was nothing surprising in their motions. … We've researched all the issues at length–even before filing our case. We look forward to responding in due course and having the judge decide.”

